SYPHILIS - AUSTRALIA (03): (SOUTH AUSTRALIA) INCREASING, CONGENITAL, INDIGENOUS PEOPLE
**************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Sun 18 Nov 2018 10:50 PM AEDT
Source: ABC (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) News [edited]
https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-11-18/sexual-health-service-centres-close-despite-rise-in-syphilis/10507512


Rates of sexually transmitted infection could rise in some of Adelaide's most disadvantaged communities in the long term because of a decision to close community sexual health clinics, a public health organisation has warned.

SHINE SA (Sexual Health Information Networking & Education South Australia) currently runs four clinics across Adelaide, which provide sexual health services, offering key advice about contraception and support to people with unplanned pregnancies and sexually transmitted infections (STIs). It is blaming a decision to close 2 suburban clinics in the city's north and south, as well as an HIV counselling service in Adelaide's CBD [central business district], on SA [South Australia] government funding cuts flagged in September's [2018] state budget.

"It is with regret that we give you this early warning of pending SHINE SA clinic closures at Davoren Park and Noarlunga, planned to occur in February 2019," the organisation said in a statement. "The sexual health sector has been one of the hardest impacted sectors."

SHINE went into more detail in a letter, telling its staff and collaborators it had lost [AUD] 547 000 [about USD 400 000] per year in funding and that "we now unfortunately find ourselves forced to close" the 2 clinics. "We fully appreciate that this significant loss of service will create difficulties for our partners, colleagues, and collaborators who have been ... working with us to deliver seamless services to people in the north and the south over many years," it said. The funding cut coincides with a syphilis outbreak being declared in Adelaide last week, which has prompted SA Health to issue an alert to medical practitioners.

Figures showed 49 people had been diagnosed with syphilis in the state's far north and west, and Eyre Peninsula, since the outbreak was declared in those areas in November 2016. A further 15 cases have been diagnosed in metropolitan Adelaide, with an increase in carriers in the past 6 months.

[A graph showing a general rise in the number of syphilis cases in Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people reported by month for the years 2011-2018 in the Australia states of South Australia, Western Australia, Northern Territory and Queensland, supplied by the Federal Department of Health, is available at the source URL above. - Mod.ML]

The government has expressed surprise at SHINE SA's decision to close clinics, conceding it had cut funding but calling on the organisation to reconsider. "Similar services interstate are operating more efficiently. We think there are more opportunities for SHINE to access Medicare revenue," health minister Stephen Wade said. "They need to think again about how they can more cost-effectively deliver services. It's a 9 per cent reduction in the grant but they're talking about a 50 per cent reduction in their clinics. I really question their decision to close the northern clinic and the southern clinic -- 2 areas where there is a particularly high socioeconomic need."

The president of the national Public Health Association's SA branch, Kate Kameniar, said the syphilis outbreak demonstrated why there was such a strong need for SHINE SA's clinics to remain open. "The risk is that we will see a resurfacing of some of the conditions and concerns we've had previously," she said. "In north Queensland, there was recently an outbreak of syphilis which has been a terrible outbreak that has spread down to South Australia and other states. Tragically, 6 babies died in that outbreak."

Mr Wade said the SA government was working with the federal government and Aboriginal health agencies to address the syphilis outbreak. He said "as far as I know" that SHINE SA was not involved in combating syphilis in the remote north west of the state, where Aboriginal health groups delivered those services.

