communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka

[The news reports above add 5 additional cases to the 44 cases of syphilis that were reported in ProMED-mail. Syphilis - Australia (02): increasing cases, congenital, indigenous 20181030.6119580 in South Australia's Far North, Eyre Peninsula, and Western regions since November 2016. Now, a further 15 cases are being reported in metropolitan Adelaide, for a total of 49 cases in South Australia. The syphilis outbreak is occurring in the Aboriginal and Torres Straight Islander people (Indigenous Australians) and cases of infectious syphilis include pregnant women with one reported case of congenital syphilis.

70 per cent of the indigenous population live outside major cities, of which about a third live in remote communities, where access to health services is likely to be poor (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indigenous_Australians): "Only 20 per cent of Aboriginal people who live in remote communities of more than 50 people have access to a doctor on a daily basis according to Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) figures from 2006. A further 41 per cent have local access to a doctor once a week or once a fortnight" (http://www.creativespirits.info/aboriginalculture/health/hospitals-doctors-health-aboriginal-people#ixzz3fk6Jag2m).

The Far North is a remote, least populated area in the north western corner of South Australia; Port Augusta is the largest community in the region (http://www.rdafn.com.au/our-region). A map showing the location of the Far North can be found at http://www.rdafn.com.au/content/images/RDAFN%20MAP.JPG. The Eyre and Western Region includes the Eyre Peninsula, a triangular peninsula, and the coastline extending west to South Australia's border with Western Australia (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regions_of_South_Australia#Far_North). The city of Adelaide is the state capital with an estimated population of over 1.3 million residents (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adelaide). A map showing the locations of the Eyre Peninsula and the city of Adelaide can be seen at https://goo.gl/maps/zKiuQz39XvD2. - Mod.ML

